In algebra, a '''locally compact field''' is a [[topological field]] whose topology forms a [[locally compact space]]<ref>{{citation|title=Functional Analysis and Valuation Theory|first=Lawrence|last=Narici|publisher=[[CRC Press]]|year=1971|isbn=9780824714840|pages=21‚Äì22|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dSGMFF3viGkC&pg=PA21}}.</ref> (in particular, it is a Hausdorff space). Examples are discrete fields and [[local field]]s such as the field of complex numbers and the ''p''-adic fields. Since one can always give discrete topology to a field, any field can be turned into a locally compact field.
