A '''polar metal''', '''metallic ferroeletric''',<ref>{{cite web|author1=Drexel University|title=Researchers open path to finding rare, polarized metals|url=http://phys.org/news/2014-04-path-rare-polarized-metals.html|website=phys.org|accessdate=23 April 2016|date=2 April 2014}}</ref> or '''ferroelectric metal'''<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Benedek|first1=Nicole A.|last2=Birol|first2=Turan|title='Ferroelectric' metals reexamined: fundamental mechanisms and design considerations for new materials|journal=Journal of Materials Chemistry C|date=2016|doi=10.1039/C5TC03856A|volume=4|issue=18|pages=4000‚Äì4015|arxiv=1511.06187|bibcode=2013JMCC....1.4300D}}</ref> is a [[metal]] that contains an [[electric dipole moment]]. Its components have an ordered electric dipole. Such metals should be unexpected, because the charge should conduct by way of the free electrons in the metal and neutralize the polarized charge. However they do exist. One substance family that can produce a polar metal is the [[nickelate]] [[perovskites]]. One example interpreted to show polar metallic behavior is [[lanthanum nickelate]], LaNiO<sub>3</sub>.<ref name=Kim>{{cite journal|last1=Kim|first1=T. H.|last2=Puggioni|first2=D.|last3=Yuan|first3=Y.|last4=Xie|first4=L.|last5=Zhou|first5=H.|last6=Campbell|first6=N.|last7=Ryan|first7=P. J.|last8=Choi|first8=Y.|last9=Kim|first9=J.-W.|last10=Patzner|first10=J. R.|last11=Ryu|first11=S.|last12=Podkaminer|first12=J. P.|last13=Irwin|first13=J.|last14=Ma|first14=Y.|last15=Fennie|first15=C. J.|last16=Rzchowski|first16=M. S.|last17=Pan|first17=X. Q.|last18=Gopalan|first18=V.|last19=Rondinelli|first19=J. M.|last20=Eom|first20=C. B.|display-authors=10|title=Polar metals by geometric design|journal=Nature|date=20 April 2016|doi=10.1038/nature17628|volume=533|issue=7601|pages=68‚Äì72|pmid=27096369|bibcode=2016Natur.533...68K}}</ref><ref name="Kumah">{{cite journal|last1=Kumah|first1=D.P.|last2=Malashevich|first2=A.|last3=Disa|first3=A.S.|last4=Arena|first4=D.A.|last5=Walker|first5=F.J.|last6=Ismail-Beigi|first6=S.|last7=Ahn|first7=C.H.|title=Effect of Surface Termination on the Electronic Properties of LaNiO<sub>3</sub> Films|journal=Physical Review Applied|date=6 November 2015|volume=2|issue=5|page=054004|doi=10.1103/PhysRevApplied.2.054004|bibcode = 2014PhRvP...2e4004K }}</ref> A thin film of LaNiO<sub>3</sub> grown on the (111) crystal face of [[lanthanum aluminate]], (LaAlO<sub>3</sub>) was interpreted to be both conductor and a polar material at room temperature.<ref name=Kim/> The resistivity of this system, however, shows an upturn with decreasing temperature, hence does not strictly adhere to the definition of a metal. Also, when grown 3 or 4 unit cells thick (1-2&nbsp;nm) on the (100) crystal face of LaAlO<sub>3</sub>, the LaNiO<sub>3</sub> can be a polar insulator or polar metal depending on the atomic termination of the surface.<ref name=Kumah/> [[Lithium osmate]],<ref>{{cite web|title=When is a ferroelectric not a ferroelectric?|url=http://www.isis.stfc.ac.uk/science/physics/magnetism/when-is-a-ferroelectric-not-a-ferroelectric14488.html|website=www.isis.stfc.ac.uk|accessdate=21 April 2016|date=2013}}</ref> LiOsO<sub>3</sub> also undergoes a [[ferrorelectric transition]] when it is cooled below 140K. The [[point group]] changes from ''R{{overline|3}}c'' to ''R3c'' losing its centrosymmetry.<ref name=Shi/> <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Paredes Aulestia|first=Esteban I.|last2=Cheung|first2=Yiu Wing|last3=Fang|first3=Yue-Wen|last4=He|first4=Jianfeng|last5=Yamaura|first5=Kazunari|last6=Lai|first6=Kwing To|last7=Goh|first7=Swee K.|last8=Chen|first8=Hanghui|date=2018-07-02|title=Pressure-induced enhancement of non-polar to polar transition temperature in metallic LiOsO3|url=https://aip.scitation.org/doi/10.1063/1.5035133|journal=Applied Physics Letters|language=en|volume=113|issue=1|pages=012902|doi=10.1063/1.5035133|issn=0003-6951}}</ref>At room temperature and below lithium osmate is an electric conductor, in single crystal, polycrystalline or powder forms, and the ferroelectric form only appears below 140K. Above 140K the material behaves like a normal metal.<ref name=Shisup>{{cite journal|last1=Shi|first1=Youguo|last2=Guo|first2=Yanfeng|last3=Wang|first3=Xia|last4=Princep|first4=Andrew J.|last5=Khalyavin|first5=Dmitry|last6=Manuel|first6=Pascal|last7=Michiue|first7=Yuichi|last8=Sato|first8=Akira|last9=Tsuda|first9=Kenji|last10=Yu|first10=Shan|last11=Arai|first11=Masao|last12=Shirako|first12=Yuichi|last13=Akaogi|first13=Masaki|last14=Wang|first14=Nanlin|last15=Yamaura|first15=Kazunari|last16=Boothroyd|first16=Andrew T.|display-authors=10|title=A ferroelectric-like structural transition in a metal supplementary information|journal=Nature Materials|date=22 September 2013|url=http://www.nature.com/nmat/journal/v12/n11/extref/nmat3754-s1.pdf|doi=10.1038/nmat3754-s1|volume=12|doi-broken-date=2018-09-06}}</ref>
[[Philip Warren Anderson|P. W. Anderson]] and E. I. Blount predicted that a ferroelectric metal could exist in 1965.<ref name="Shi">{{cite journal|last1=Shi|first1=Youguo|last2=Guo|first2=Yanfeng|last3=Wang|first3=Xia|last4=Princep|first4=Andrew J.|last5=Khalyavin|first5=Dmitry|last6=Manuel|first6=Pascal|last7=Michiue|first7=Yuichi|last8=Sato|first8=Akira|last9=Tsuda|first9=Kenji|display-authors=10|date=|year=1024|title=A ferroelectric-like structural transition in a metal|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nmat3754|journal=Nature Materials|volume=12|issue=11|pages=1024‚Äì1027|arxiv=1509.01849|bibcode=2013NatMa..12.1024S|doi=10.1038/nmat3754|pmid=24056805|via=|last10=Yu|first10=Shan|last11=Arai|first11=Masao|last12=Shirako|first12=Yuichi|last13=Akaogi|first13=Masaki|last14=Wang|first14=Nanlin|last15=Yamaura|first15=Kazunari|last16=Boothroyd|first16=Andrew T.}}</ref> They were inspired to make this prediction based on superconducting transitions, and the ferroelectric transition in [[barium titanate]]. The prediction was that atoms do not move far and only a slight crystal non-symmetrical deformation occurs, say from cubic to tetragonal. This transition they called martensitic. They suggested looking at [[sodium tungsten bronze]] and [[InTl]] alloy. They realised that the free electrons in the metal would neutralise the effect of the polarization at a global level, but that the conduction electrons do not strongly affect transverse optical phonons, or the local electric field inherent in [[ferroelectricity]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Anderson|first1=P. W.|last2=Blount|first2=E. I.|title=Symmetry Considerations on Martensitic Transformations: "Ferroelectric" Metals?|journal=Physical Review Letters|date=15 February 1965|volume=14|issue=7|pages=217‚Äì219|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.14.217|bibcode = 1965PhRvL..14..217A }}</ref>
